The short answer: The MainActivity should not handle navigation logic, it should only configure the navigation container.

In a perfect implementation, your MainActivity should have almost zero navigation logic.

1. The Distinction: Container vs. Content
To understand why, we have to look at who "owns" the UI elements:

The Activity owns the "Chrome": The Activity owns the NavHostFragment (the container) and the BottomNavigationView (the global menu). These elements exist outside of your individual screens.

The Fragments own the "Content": The specific screens (Home, Browse, Login) live inside the container.

Because the BottomNavigationView belongs to the Activity layout, the Activity must be the one to initialize it. However, "initializing" is different from "handling logic."

2. Critique of your current MainActivity
Let's look at your MainActivity.kt again.

The "Correct" Part (Configuration):

Kotlin

// This is GOOD. This is strictly configuration.
// It tells the system: "If the user clicks menu item X, look for destination X in the graph."
binding.bottomNavigation.setupWithNavController(navController)
This line is automagic. It requires no "logic." If your menu ID is homeFragment and your nav graph destination is homeFragment, the library handles the click, the back stack, and the highlighting automatically.

The "Questionable" Part (Logic):

Kotlin

// This is what you are rightfully questioning
binding.bottomNavigation.setOnItemSelectedListener { item ->
 when (item.itemId) {
 R.id.navigation_home -> { ... } // Manual navigation
 R.id.navigation_my_events -> { ... } // "Not implemented" logic
 // ...
 }
}
Why is this here? In your current code, this block exists primarily to intercept clicks for features that don't exist yet (navigation_my_events, navigation_updates).

Is this bad?

For a prototype: No, it's a convenient way to show "Coming Soon."

For a finished app: Yes. You should generally remove this listener entirely.

3. The Best Practice: The "Silent" MainActivity
In a fully mature production app, your setupNavigation() method in MainActivity should essentially look like this:

Kotlin

private fun setupNavigation() {
 val navHostFragment = supportFragmentManager
 .findFragmentById(R.id.navHostFragment) as NavHostFragment
 navController = navHostFragment.navController

 // 1. Link BottomNav to NavController
 // This handles ALL navigation for the bottom tabs automatically.
 binding.bottomNavigation.setupWithNavController(navController)

 // 2. Global UI Visibility
 // This is purely UI logic: "When on login screen, hide the tabs."
 // This belongs here because the Activity owns the visibility of its own child (the bottom bar).
 navController.addOnDestinationChangedListener { _, destination, _ ->
 val shouldShowBottomNav = when (destination.id) {
 R.id.splashFragment,
 R.id.loginFragment,
 R.id.registerFragment -> false
 else -> true
 }
 binding.bottomNavigation.visibility = if (shouldShowBottomNav) View.VISIBLE else View.GONE
 }
}
Notice what is missing? There is no setOnItemSelectedListener. There is no navController.navigate(...) calls inside the Activity.

Summary: When should the Activity navigate?
The Activity should never decide when to navigate based on business logic (e.g., "User clicked login button").

It should only configure the structural navigation:

Deep Linking: The Activity receives the deep link Intent from Android OS and passes it to the NavController.

Global UI Wiring: Connecting the Toolbar or BottomNav to the NavController.

Your intuition is correct: Ideally, you will delete that setOnItemSelectedListener block once those missing fragments are created. The setupWithNavController line alone is sufficient to handle the tab switching.
